title: Fragmentation cross sections of medium-energy 35Cl, 40Ar and 48Ti beams on elemental targets

x4freetext: Fragmentation cross sections of medium-energy 35Cl,
40Ar and 48Ti beams on elemental targets

x4codes.hlp: Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA, United States of America
Nat.Inst. for Quantum & Radiol.Sci.& Tech., Chiba, Japan
Chalmers Univ. of Tech., Gothenburg, Sweden

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.77, p.034605 (2008)

x4codes.hlp: Nat.Inst. for Quantum & Radiol.Sci.& Tech., Chiba, Japan
Brookhaven National Laboratory, Upton, NY, United States of America

x4freetext: Samples with natural composition were used.
Target depth (thickness) varied between 2.7 and 43%
of interaction length  typical values were
between 5 and 15% of interaction length.
C   - 4g/cm**2
Al  - 2g/cm**2
Three pairs of position sensitive Si(Li)
detectors with depth/active radius of 3mm/1.1cm,
5mm/1.9cm and 0.85-1.0mm/2cm were used. Position
data were not used.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: Systematic uncertainties dominate the total.
Statistical uncertainties are negligible.
Sources of systematic uncertainties include
-lack of precision in determination particle energy
at point of interaction
-placement of cuts in data analysis
-losses due to nuclear interaction in the detector
-limited precision in target density
Each of these sources were estimated on the order of
1%. Additional uncertainty are due to variation of
beam parameters, typicaly around 5%.
